Your task is to write a Jest test case that exposes a specific mutation in a JavaScript/TypeScript project.

MUTATION DETAILS
The mutation affects the following file:
throughs/through.js
Here is the full content of that file (shown with a <PLACEHOLDER> marker):
'use strict'

//a pass through stream that doesn't change the value.
module.exports = function through (op, onEnd) {
  var a = false

  function once (abort) {
    if(a || !onEnd) return
    a = true
       <PLACEHOLDER>

  }

  return function (read) {
    return function (end, cb) {
      if(end) once(end)
      return read(end, function (end, data) {
        if(!end) op && op(data)
        else once(end)
        cb(end, data)
      })
    }
  }
}

In the original code, <PLACEHOLDER> has the value:

-       onEnd(abort === true ? null : abort)
In the mutated code, <PLACEHOLDER> has the value:

+       onEnd(abort === false ? null : abort)


YOUR TASK
Write one Jest test file that:
    1. Passes when run against the original code.
    2. Fails when run against the mutated code.
    3. Tests the behavior of the mutated file in a way that reliably detects the mutation.
The test will be saved at the following path, relative to this test-generation project’s root:
llm-cache/anthropic_claude-sonnet-4.6/temp_0.5/withoutTests/cached/artifacts/pull-stream/attempt_1/pending_category/mutant-2403a14/testCase.test.ts

ALLOWED LIBRARIES
You may use:
    1. Any built-in Node.js modules (e.g., fs, path, crypto, etc.).

You may not use any other third-party libraries.

Looking at the mutation, the difference is:
- Original: `onEnd(abort === true ? null : abort)` - when `abort` is `true`, passes `null` to `onEnd`
- Mutated: `onEnd(abort === false ? null : abort)` - when `abort` is `false`, passes `null` to `onEnd`

The key behavioral difference: when the stream ends normally (abort = `true`), the original calls `onEnd(null)`, but the mutated version calls `onEnd(true)`. When there's an actual error object, the original passes the error, but the mutated version also passes it correctly (since an error object is neither `true` nor `false`).

So I need to test that when a stream ends normally (with `true`), `onEnd` receives `null`.

```typescript
import through from "../../../../../../../../../../../subject_repositories/pull-stream/throughs/through.js";

describe("through onEnd callback", () => {
  it("should call onEnd with null when stream ends normally (abort === true)", (done) => {
    const receivedArgs: any[] = [];

    const onEnd = (err: any) => {
      receivedArgs.push(err);
    };

    const throughStream = through(undefined, onEnd);

    // Create a simple source that ends after one item
    let count = 0;
    const source = (end: any, cb: (end: any, data?: any) => void) => {
      if (end || count >= 1) {
        cb(true, null);
        return;
      }
      count++;
      cb(null, count);
    };

    const sink = throughStream(source);

    // Read first item
    sink(null, (end: any, data: any) => {
      if (!end) {
        // Read again to get the end signal
        sink(null, (end2: any, data2: any) => {
          // Stream ended, onEnd should have been called with null
          expect(receivedArgs.length).toBe(1);
          expect(receivedArgs[0]).toBe(null);
          done();
        });
      }
    });
  });
});
```
